---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Store Policy — Saturday Boring Cereal">
  <div class="light"></div>
  <h1 class="pagetitle">STORE POLICY</h1>
  <p class="pagesub">The methodology, posted by the register where nobody reads it.</p>

  <div class="policy wrap">
    <section>
      <h2>§1 — The Taste Scale</h2>
      <p>
        Every cereal is scored 0–10, decimals allowed. The scale is inherited from years of
        careful record-keeping and will not be changed, recalibrated, or explained. An 8.5 is a
        very good morning. Nothing has earned a 10. Nothing may ever earn a 10.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>§2 — The Numbers</h2>
      <p>
        Nutrition is transcribed from the physical box and cross-checked against USDA FoodData
        Central where possible. Values are per stated serving. When a label doesn't state a value
        — protein %DV, poly/mono fats, added sugars — this store prints <em>“not listed”</em>
        rather than inventing a number. The FDA only requires protein %DV when a protein claim is
        made; most boxes stay quiet, and so do we.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>§3 — What Gets Shelved</h2>
      <p>
        Granolas and healthier cereals, weighted toward things a functioning adult eats on
        purpose: flakes, clusters, high-fiber, high-protein. Neon marshmallow products are outside
        the jurisdiction of this regulatory body.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>§4 — On Clusters</h2>
      <p>
        Flakes are only acceptable when accompanied by clusters. This is store policy. Complaints
        may be filed with the spoon.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>§5 — Returns</h2>
      <p>All opinions are final. No refunds. Total regret: 0.00.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="overall">
      <h2>§6 — The Overall Grade</h2>
      <p>
        The Taste score answers one question: is it good. The <em>Overall grade</em> answers a
        nosier one — is it good <em>for you</em>, too. It is one part the spoon's verdict and one
        part the box's own numbers, split fifty-fifty with no thumb on the scale. Protein and fiber
        help; sugar hurts; only the figures printed on the label are admitted as evidence. A cereal
        that tastes like a birthday but eats like dessert lands mid-pack, and a virtuous brick
        nobody enjoys does no better. Grades run A to F, handed out like a strict lunchroom: an A is
        rare, and — see §1 — a perfect score remains impossible. Unrated boxes get no grade, because
        we will not invent a taste we never had. The formula lives in the code, not on this poster;
        change a target and every box on the shelf is re-graded at once.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .pagetitle {
    text-align: center;
    font-size: 30px;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    margin-top: 30px;
  }

  .pagesub {
    text-align: center;
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 13.5px;
    color: #6b4a2a;
    margin-top: 6px;
  }

  .policy {
    max-width: 640px;
    margin-top: 34px;
    background: #fffdf4;
    border: 1px solid #e0d5b8;
    box-shadow: 0 10px 26px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12);
    padding: 30px 34px;
  }

  section + section {
    margin-top: 22px;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: 13px;
    letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--red);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 14.5px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #3d2c15;
  }
</style>
